   - Ensure that the application checks whether the user has permission to access the requested user data. This could involve checking user roles or ownership of the resource.
   ```javascript
   app.get('/user', (req, res) => {
       const userId = req.query.id;
       // Assuming req.user contains the authenticated user's information
       if (req.user.id !== userId) {
           return res.status(403).send('Access denied');
       }
       db.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?', [userId], (err, results) => {
           if (err) {
               return res.status(500).send('Database error');
           }
           res.json(results);
       });
   });
   ```

### Conclusion
By implementing parameterized queries and proper access control checks, you can significantly reduce the risk of SQL injection and unauthorized access to user data, thus addressing the identified vulnerabilities in the Express.js route.
